The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox,” writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick, author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in case of claims to the health status of the potential customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not take out insurance.
Some time ago the client had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the result of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure 10 years ago: based on the customer's identification code, you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines he has bought in the last year and a half, and from this the program reveals what diseases he suffers and what health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that the level of fat in the blood is practically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the drawbacks is that some medications are usable for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the point of view of insurance - commercial, is valid as a risk factor, the first two are not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are now obliging them to do so even though they have not imposed fines for negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time control of usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
Before Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this he has developed a program that links the transmission of data with the express approval of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny the approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
